<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
5.0 mm long (n = 1); 2.17
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as long as wide. This species is distinguished from all other species in Southeast Asia, except the Malaysian species, 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. glauca" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="glauca">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">A. glauca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Sampson, 1921), by the completely divided eye. It is easily distinguished from 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. glauca" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="glauca">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">A. glauca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the presence of a small tooth on the first interstriae at the top of the declivity, the impressed declivital striae, and densely punctured declivital interstriae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
